      <hedline>
        <hl1>Vieques Island</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lisa Mullenneaux letter on Claudia Dreifus' April 9 travel article holds demonstrations at US Navy's firing range on Viesques Island, Puerto Rico, gives vacationers unusual opportunity to learn about island's recent history</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Rather than cause a nuisance, the acts of civil disobedience on the Navy's firing range  on Vieques give vacationers an  unusual opportunity to learn about an important, and evolving, piece of the island's recent history. In fact, protesters camped at the entrance to Camp Garcia welcome visitors' interest and questions about that history.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Rather than cause a nuisance, the acts of civil disobedience on the Navy's firing range  on Vieques give vacationers an  unusual opportunity to learn about an important, and evolving, piece of the island's recent history. In fact, protesters camped at the entrance to Camp Garcia welcome visitors' interest and questions about that history.</p>
        <p>But that opportunity wasn't the only one the author and her friend passed up. She couldn't find a Puerto Rican meal? This island is so small that anyone who asks for Olga is immediately directed to home-cooked native food served at the Posada Vista Mar, a few short blocks from where the author dined.</p>
        <p>LISA MULLENNEAUX  New York, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
